english:
  title: Record of the Inkstone Hermitage at Fragrant Mountain
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Fragrant Mountain stands on the southern shore of the Yalu River, north of Pyongyang, forming a boundary with Liaodong. The mountain's grandeur knows no equal, a spur of the great Long White Mountain itself. It abounds with fragrant woods and evergreens, and traces of ancient sages and Buddhas linger there. The mountain bears its name for the fragrance it holds... a sacred ground for the Buddha's Way. The venerable Boeje once dwelt there, and when he passed into nirvana, his disciple Seungji brought his relics to rest upon this mountain. Kakjeong, also a disciple of Boeje, discovered the ancient site and built a small hall—three columns and nothing more. Yet in this simplicity, they enshrined the master's likeness in the hall's center, where morning and evening prayers are faithfully offered.

    When the monk Jiseon came bearing Kakjeong's request that I compose this record, I told him: "Kakjeong's face escapes my memory, and his words reach my ears only through your voice. What harm if you forget what he asked? Even without his request, the venerable Boeje's legacy speaks for itself. I know Boeje—what concern have I with others?" Thus I took up my brush.

    Boeje's disciples are countless, yet those who labor after his passing to inscribe monuments and preserve his memory in these halls—seeking his immortality—they follow one upon another. All join without regard to rank or wisdom, becoming one, unbreakable. What force compels this? Is it not like hounds that bay at the sight and sound of one another, an inevitable necessity of their nature? When frost falls, the bell rings; when a stone touches water, it responds. In this way of cause and effect, things occur beyond our will. Boeje's legacy must have its source in the Way itself.

    Look how the Buddhist faithful have grown to near half the realm. Tracing back centuries, the Way has flourished ever more. Yet among those who have left this world, few have left such distinction as Boeje. How well his contemporaries honored him with devoted hearts! While he lived, critics abounded; yet upon his passing, they follow him still with such fervor. Ah, whose hand truly guides the human heart?

    So I speak this to Jiseon, and through him to Kakjeong: let your reverence deepen, and in preserving your master's relics, exercise ever greater care. The mountain's beauty, the monks often sing of it—but I grow old and shall not walk its paths. Still, I record this memory.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Boeje (普濟) was a renowned Buddhist master of the Goryeo period, celebrated for his virtue and influence.
  - key: ''
    value: The relics (舍利) refer to the cremated remains of the Buddha or his disciples, venerated as sacred objects.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three columns' symbolize the humble but sincere nature of the memorial hall, suggesting that spiritual authenticity transcends architectural grandeur.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Saek employs the image of frost and bell, stone and water to illustrate the Buddhist principle of dependent origination and natural responsiveness.
  - key: ''
    value: The paradox Lee Saek presents—that Boeje faced criticism in life yet devotion after death—reflects his deeper meditation on the inconsistency of human judgment and the eventual triumph of virtue.
